ce:section.ce:para:
To demonstrate the feasibility of all samples as a nanocarrier, drug encapsulation efficiency and release behaviors were determined based on the measuring of PTX concentration as a drug model. Significant variations in the characteristic absorption spectra of PTX/nanocarrier supernatant could be evidence of the successful loading of PTX onto the nanocarriers owing to the suitable attachment region of nanocarrier structure with drug functional groups through π-π stacking interactions or hydrogen bonds (Fig. 9
                        ). By this method, the concentration of PTX was measured before and after loading into the NPs by calculating the absorption intensity of drug at 235 nm wavelength using the standard calibration curve. The obtained results for PTX loading capacity and encapsulation efficiency of the various batches of nanocarriers within 72 h were illustrated in Table 1
                         which are comparable to previous reports [46,47,60–62]. It was notable that, the N- GQDs/CoFe2O4/LDH offered the higher encapsulation efficiency and loading of PTX than other samples (88% and 31%, respectively). It could be inferred that the encapsulation efficiency of PTX is affected by some factors including the proportion of NPs, the size effect of the samples, high surface-to-volume ratio and the amount of PTX. The high loading ability of the N-GQDs/CoFe2O4/LDH with the hydrophobic drug as compared to other samples is due to the modification of CoFe2O4/LDH surface with GQDs functionalized, PEG and various interactions with PTX such as H-bonding, π-π stacking, covalent and electrostatic which makes it potential in the treatment of cancer, while these interactions for CoFe2O4/LDH and LDH have lower powerful.
